<DOC><DOCNO> AP890413-0084 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1027EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Prison 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0313</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Prison, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0320</SECOND><HEAD>Police Foil Hostage Incident at Prison; Kill Inmate</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with incident over, hostages safe. ADDSbyline.</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two armed inmates seized eight hostages at ahigh-security prison and were allowed to leave the facility, butpolice killed one and wounded the other when the men threatened tokill a captive, Tass said today.   The official news agency said all the hostages were freedunharmed.   Armed with ``self-made firearms and knives,'' the two mensneaked into the administrative building at the high-securityprison colony in the Voroshilovgrad region of the Ukraine at 10:30a.m. Wednesday. They took eight female employees hostage, theofficial news agency said.   Tass said the inmates barricaded themselves in the building anddemanded a bus and guarantees they would be allowed to leave thecolony, 500 miles south of Moscow.   During negotiations with regional police and KGB chiefs, theinmates were persuaded to release two captives, ``but the criminalswouldn't set the others free unless authorities agreed to theirdemands,'' Tass said.   It identified the inmates as V. Maximov serving a 15-year termfor murder and theft, and O. Korzh sentenced to eight years inprison for robbery and malicious hooliganism. It said both wererepeat offenders.   After authorities decided to meet the criminals' demands, a bustook them and their remaining hostages out of the penal colony.Negotiators tried again to negotiate with the men before the busreached the highway, Tass said.   The criminals demanded the release of another inmate andthreatened to kill one of the hostages immediately if that wasn'tdone. After negotiations failed, authorities decided to attack,Tass said.   ``A carefully planned operation sprang into life,'' it said.``Korzh was killed on the spot and Maximov wounded.''   Tass said the situation had returned to normal at the prison.</TEXT></DOC>